Trading Journal Phase 1 — implementation log (for future loops)

WHY denormalized derived columns (ticks/gross_pnl/net_pnl stored on the row):
- stats endpoint aggregates in SQL (SUM/COUNT/AVG) with no per-row Python;
- each row is a stable historical snapshot next to the exact tick_size/tick_value
  used, so editing a future trade never rewrites past P&L;
- frontend renders authoritative numbers without re-deriving.
Drift is prevented because controllers/trade.py is the ONLY write path and always
recomputes via compute_pnl on create/update; there is no API to set them directly.

THE ONE CONVENTION (identical in backend compute_pnl, frontend pnl.ts, all tests):
  direction   = +1 long / -1 short
  ticks_moved = (exit_price - entry_price) / tick_size     # signed by price
  ticks       = ticks_moved * direction                    # per-contract, signed by P&L
  gross_pnl   = ticks * tick_value * contracts             # multiplier hits DOLLARS ONLY
  net_pnl     = gross_pnl - fees
Canonical: ES long 5000->5010, tick 0.25, $12.5/tick, 2 contracts, $4.5 fees =>
ticks 40, gross 1000.00, net 995.50. Do NOT multiply ticks by contracts.

DECISIONS / GOTCHAS worth remembering:
- Money precision: SQLAlchemy Numeric + Python Decimal everywhere; quantize to
  column scales on write (_TICKS_Q/_MONEY_Q = 0.0001).
- compute_stats: SQLite returns float from SUM over Numeric; Postgres returns
  Decimal. _dec() routes every aggregate through str() so Decimal stays exact
  (Decimal(float) would inject binary-float noise). Empty journal => all zeros,
  win_rate/avg_win/avg_loss guarded against divide-by-zero. scratch (net==0) is
  neither win nor loss; win_rate denominator is total trades.
- Datetimes stored naive-UTC (models._utcnow + controller _to_naive_utc) so
  SQLite and Postgres DateTime columns round-trip identically.
- TradeResponse/StatsResponse fields are float (not Decimal) so model_dump(mode=
  'json') emits plain JSON numbers matching the spec examples; Decimal in the DB
  remains the source of truth. Tests assert with tolerance.
- View emits its own 400 (with fields map) and 404 JSON directly rather than
  abort(), so the fields map and JSON content-type are deterministic regardless
  of the request Accept header. errors.py stays the fallback for unrouted paths.
- Schema uses extra='ignore' so client-sent ticks/gross_pnl/net_pnl are dropped.
- Validator messages are terse ("must be greater than 0"); the view strips the
  Pydantic "Value error, " prefix when building the fields map.

FRONTEND lint/type gotchas (this repo's config):
- tsconfig includes only "src"; frontend tests are NOT tsc/eslint checked.
- eslint (js.configs.recommended, no typescript-eslint recommended) fires
  no-undef on TS-only globals: import type { FormEvent, ReactNode } from 'react'
  instead of React.X; type fetch's init as Parameters<typeof fetch>[1] instead of
  naming RequestInit.
- pnl.ts is float math (display-only preview) — its fractional-ticks test asserts
  with toBeCloseTo, not exact equality (backend Decimal is authoritative).
- Form controls have name="<field>" so Playwright/tests select them reliably.

RUN/VALIDATION:
- Backend needs the trades table: flask db upgrade (env exported) or script/setup.
- E2E: npx playwright test --reporter=list (default html reporter hangs agents);
  it persists a real row to the dev Postgres DB.
- All green: pytest 42, vitest 23, playwright 2, mypy strict + tsc, flake8 + eslint.

Phase 2 (NOT built): broker/CSV import, instruments table + auto-fill, open
positions (nullable exit + status), multi-user/auth, charts. compute_pnl is
designed to remain the single source of truth for imported trades too.
